    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Hibbertia bracteata improperly include developing skin irritation and skin irritations due to its toxicity, which is caused by the presence of sesquiterpenoid compounds. These compounds can also cause allergic reactions in some individuals, potentially leading to anaphylaxis, a severe and life-threatening condition. Ingesting large amounts of the plant may cause gastrointestinal issues, such as diarrhea, due to its irritant properties on the mucous membranes. Furthermore, it can induce vomiting as the body attempts to eliminate the toxic substances. Additionally, improper use may lead to more severe reactions, including organ damage and death, especially in vulnerable populations such as children and pregnant women.",
    "uses": "Hibbertia bracteata, also known as the rusty cup, is native to Western Australia. It has been traditionally used by Indigenous Australians for its medicinal properties. Research has shown that Hibbertia bracteata contains various compounds with potential antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activities. However, further studies are needed to confirm its efficacy and safety for human use. Its potential medicinal uses are still being explored by scientists, but initial findings suggest it may have benefits for treating certain health conditions.",
    "taxonomy": "Hibbertia bracteata is classified in the family Dilleniaceae. This plant is native to Australia, and its classification is a part of the broader botanical classification. At the kingdom level, it belongs to Plantae, and at the order level, it is part of Dilleniales. The classification of Hibbertia bracteata is an essential aspect of understanding its evolutionary history and relationships with other plants. By examining its classification, researchers can gain insights into the plant's characteristics and behavior.",
    "benefits": "Hibbertia bracteata, also known as the small yellow codon, has been studied for its potential health benefits, including antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. Its extracts have shown to have antimicrobial and antifungal activities, which may contribute to its potential in treating various infections. The plant may also have antiviral properties, although more research is needed to confirm its effectiveness. Additionally, Hibbertia bracteata contains flavonoids, which have been linked to cardiovascular health and may help protect against certain diseases. While more studies are required to fully understand its health benefits, initial findings suggest potential applications in traditional medicine.",
    "parts": "Hibbertia bracteata, also known as the yellow peely, is a plant native to Western Australia, and its leaves are reported to be used in traditional medicine. The leaves are said to have anti-inflammatory properties. Research has shown that the plant may be used to treat various health conditions, including arthritis and other inflammatory diseases. However, further studies are needed to fully understand its medicinal potential. The leaves are also believed to have antioxidant properties, which may contribute to their therapeutic effects.",
    "intro": "Hibbertia bracteata, also known as the Guinea flower, is a small, shrub-like plant native to Australia, belonging to the family Dilleniaceae. The Guinea flower has been traditionally used in herbal medicine to treat various health conditions, including anxiety, insomnia, and inflammation, due to its purported health benefits. The bioactive constituents of Hibbertia bracteata include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. The plant is commonly used to make teas, capsules, and tinctures, which are often marketed as supplements to promote relaxation, reduce stress, and improve overall well-being."
